[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### A4 - LOW: The TTL on DynamoDB Records Is Set to 45 Days but Outcome Tracking Runs at Day 30-31
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Location:** Step 4 pseudocode, `ttl: discharge_info.discharge_date + 45 days`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Issue:** The TTL is set to 45 days (15 days past the 30-day window). The outcome tracking in Step 5 queries for patients discharged 30-31 days ago. This leaves only a 14-day buffer between outcome recording and TTL expiration. If the outcome tracking job fails for 2 weeks (not impossible during system migrations or holiday staffing), records will be deleted before outcomes are recorded, creating gaps in the training data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Suggested fix:** Consider extending TTL to 90 days, or better, archive scored records to S3 (Parquet) before TTL expiration. The S3 archive serves as the training data source for model retraining and is not subject to DynamoDB TTL. Add: "Archive all scored records with outcomes to S3 weekly. The DynamoDB table serves real-time operational lookups; S3 serves model retraining and retrospective analysis."
